When Kennedy announced that the US was going to get to the moon in 10 years Nasa representatives were horrified. They had better plans of a far reaching kind to steadily explore and expand into all space. They knew the score. The blatant political stunt of 'beating the Russians to the moon' which was recently revealed in the Kennedy tapes was no secret to them and they fully realised the implications. <br>
<br>
We sold out the space age in favour of a flag ceremony on the moon. A handful of high priced tickets to Luna. Starting in 69 and finishing in 72. That was it. The space age died before it had even begun. We rode a few big fireworks to our natural satellite and then called it a day after the cost of these insane contraptions started to hit the publics awareness.<br>
<br>
I find the idea of momentum exchange very interesting. It's like an Orion in reverse. A pulse drive using external pulse units. Seems quite feasible to me. The only draw back I can see is that several technologies have to be developed further. It can be done but a lot of work maybe. With decent funding how long do you think it would take to develop this idea to the flight stage?   <br>
<br>
Like all the technologies discussed here it is similarly hampered by it's use of nuclear power. If the restraints on nuclear concepts were entirely lifted then there would be numerous ways of reaching space and once there we could begin construction of larger designs. Using nuclear power there really is no limit to what we could accomplish. <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
