<br>
&gt; I'm sceptical of momentum exchange mainly because I don't like the idea of a projectile hitting the craft at high speeds.<br>
<br>
 That's the beauty of tethered momentum exchange (not necessarily similar to what &quot;crwillis&quot; meant): incoming packages don't come in at high speeds, as a practical concern --once you've gotten the orbital mechanics right by having the package at the right time/place.<br>
 The tether tip is moving at (for instance) 1.5km/sec relative to the center of mass (&quot;ballast&quot; ship/station), and in this example, the incoming payload is also moving at 1.5km/sec relative to the ballast. That means that the relative speeds of the closing parts (payload &amp; tether tip) are near zero.<br>
 Perhaps you mean that if you get orbital mechanics wrong, an off-course load could come at the ship... With the exceptions of early Lunar probes, the phuck-up by Lock-Mart which killed that Mars probe, and the Progress ship which rammed Mir, we've got things nailed down pretty solidly. With a proven system, and some corrective delta-V on the packages and tether tip catcher, I'd bet on it.<br>
<br>
 Whatever this &quot;Nuclear Powered Momentum Exchange&quot; is, I'd hope practical issues are worked out similarly.<br>
<br>
 Another application for a tether system; launching probes from a ship. Save reaction mass for probes &amp; such by using a tether attached to the ship (even if it's an Orion). Throw things out of plane or to different orbits. A mass driver might benice too. Send probes out, or send re-supply loads down to Mars explorers. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1999.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 55<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/19/02 12:04:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What's your favourite Nuclear Rocket Concept?</span><hr size=1> I think you are talking about a liquid core nuclear rocket<br>
